node.text: Experiments that demonstrate 3D printing with dust, use engineered tissue to study muscle loss, and analyze growth of slime mold, along with other scientific studies and supplies, are headed to the International Space Station on Northrop Grumman’s 16th commercial resupply services mission (NG CRS-16). Launch of the Cygnus spacecraft is targeted for August 10 from NASA’s Wallops Flight Facility in Virginia.

node.title: 3D Printing, Muscle Cells, and Mold Experiments Launching to Space Station

node.text: This morning at 6:55 a.m. EDT the Pirs docking compartment, with the attached Progress 77 spacecraft, separated from the Space Station that had been its home for the past 20 years. #nasa #roscosmos #pirs #progress77 #progress #spacestation

node.text: The SpaceX Crew Dragon Endeavour, with Crew-2 astronauts aboard, undocked from Harmony's forward-facing port at 6:45am ET and relocated to the space-facing port to re-docked to the station 7:35 am ET, completing the second space station port change for the crewed spacecraft.

node.text: The SpaceX Cargo Dragon undocked from the space station today at 10:45 a.m. EDT. Astronaut Shane Kimbrough thanked the ground crews that supported Cargo Dragon operations as the U.S. spacecraft headed to the Gulf of Mexico for a splashdown on Friday.

node.title: Astronaut Shane Kimbrough Thanks Cargo Dragon Operations Personnel

node.text: The SpaceX Cargo Dragon vehicle launched at 1:29 p.m. EDT today toward the space station. It will deliver 7,300 pounds of new science, supplies and solar arrays on Saturday at 5 a.m. live on NASA TV.

node.text: Experiments that demonstrate 3D printing with dust, use engineered tissue to study muscle loss, and analyze growth of slime mold, along with other scientific studies and supplies, are headed to the International Space Station on Northrop Grumman’s 16th commercial resupply services mission (NG CRS-16). Launch of the Cygnus spacecraft is targeted for August 10 from NASA’s Wallops Flight Facility in Virginia.

node.text:
🚀 Liftoff! 🚀 A new module is on its way to the space station. It will serve as a future science facility, docking port, and spacewalk airlock.

It’s called the Multipurpose Laboratory Module, nicknamed “Nauka,” the Russian word for science.

node.text: The SpaceX Crew Dragon Endeavour, with Crew-2 astronauts aboard, undocked from Harmony's forward-facing port at 6:45am ET and relocated to the space-facing port to re-docked to the station 7:35 am ET, completing the second space station port change for the crewed spacecraft.

node.text: Expedition 65 Flight Engineer Thomas Pesquet of ESA (European Space Agency) conducts a session for the InSPACE-4 physics study. node.text:
Things are heating up in space! 🔥 
Aboard the International Space Station, researchers recently created cool flames, which burn at extremely low temperatures, and are nearly impossible to create in Earth’s gravity. This was the first time spherical cool diffusion flames have been observed burning gases. Depicted here is a hot flame created in a test similar to the ones that generated the cool flames. Studying cool flames could lead to cleaner, more efficient internal combustion engines.
 
In this video, soot that forms at ignition escapes from the hot flame, increasing the heat loss experienced by the flame. This causes it to locally quench, creating a hole in the flame and enhancing flammability. As a result, the flame reforms, closing the hole, but it opens again due to heat loss. This repeated opening and closing of the flame creates a dramatic flame that swirls around the burner. Cool flames were created in similar tests last month.
